European Defense and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that the occupation by the Nazis.
Perhaps it is due to the experience of living in a country in the center of Europe, a place that has been for centuries a crossroads of intellectual currents, geopolitical interests, and European confrontations.
Perhaps all these factors, combined together, have led me to the conviction that Europe represents a single political entity, whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could forever be two Europes  one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, and one less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated  is a mistake.
That is as if one part of a room could be heated while it remained cold in the other part.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event evokes an echo across Europe.
If Europe is to become one, if the European Union is to absorb the new post-communist democracies  which is in Europe's interest , a series of essential tasks must be addressed, within the new democracies as well as in the European and Atlantic communities.
First, Europe must promote community within the post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
Because a living society cannot be rebuilt from above.
Europe must therefore help its new democracies become an organic part of a common continental commitment to deepen and strengthen civil society.
The more diverse European civil society structures become and the more interconnected they are, the better equipped the new democracies will be for EU membership and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer diverse solidarity tasks to self-administered institutions and non-profit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution is, the more transparent and economical it will be; and the better it will satisfy those social needs that central authorities cannot recognize.
Social solidarity becomes more authentic when it is closely linked to people or their associations.
Authentic solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the surest foundation for those forms of solidarity that can only be exercised by states.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was appeasement policy with its abandonment of European solidarity, which led to the capitulation of Munich.
This experience is still a powerful call for vigilance.
The evil must be confronted as soon as it appears, but it is not enough if only governments act.
Because government policy emerges from the feelings of civil society, from the people.
Concern for security is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is working intensively on a new concept of its security policy.
It should be distinguished by the ability to make quick decisions and to swiftly implement communal decisions  reforms that have proven necessary due to recent developments in Yugoslavia.
The NATO intervention last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom, as well as the concerns of pan-European security, require interventions beyond EU borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action is, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations in which the UN mandate may not come, even though an intervention would be in the interest of many people, all of Europe, yes, even human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared for it, at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical preparedness.
But further things are still needed in the field of preventive security, but it is also more necessary to ensure that this security reflects the values of the expanded civil society of Europe.
Tens of thousands of human lives and an enormous amount of material could have been saved in Kosovo, in Bosnia and Herzegovina and in other parts of the former Yugoslavia, if the international community had acted at the beginning of the conflict.
Despite warnings about impending horror, action was only timid.
These failures were the result of diverse individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still be watching the horror in Kosovo.
Europe cannot remain forever dependent on the USA, especially not with regard to European problems.
It must be able to agree on its own solutions.
It is unthinkable that the EU can exist as a respected part of the world order if it proves incapable of agreeing on means and ways to protect human rights, not only on its territory, but also in areas that may one day join it.
Such an EU enlargement is only justifiable if it proceeds hand in hand with a courageous reform of EU institutions.
I confidently hope that the government conference on institutional reform will present practical proposals to advance the Union.
But I see this as the beginning of a process that may take decades and should be guided by a lasting effort to speed up and make EU decision-making more transparent.
An issue connected to institutional reform is the question of how to give smaller states the assurance that they will not simply be outvoted by the larger ones, while still duly taking into account the size of individual states.
One possibility is the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber would not be directly elected, but would be chosen by the parliaments of the member states from their own ranks.
The first chamber of the EU  that is, the current parliament  would thus reflect the size of individual member states, while the second chamber would, with the same number of representatives for each state, increase equality.
Sooner or later, these changes will require the EU to have a clear, understandable constitution  a text that all European children could learn.
Such a constitution would require two parts.
Part one would define the rights and duties of both European citizens and states, the underlying values, and the significance and goals of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their principle competences, and their relationships with each other.
Such a basic law would not automatically transform the current Union into the federal superstate feared by Eurosceptics.
It would, however, help citizens in an integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, understand it better, see the significance of the EU for their lives, and, consequently, identify with it.
